
[1]sterling

   STERLING, a. [probably from Easterling.]

   1. An epithet by which English money of account is distinguished; as a
   pound sterling; a shilling sterling; a penny sterling. It is not now
   applied to the coins of England; but sterling cost, sterling value are
   used.

   2. Genuine; pure; of excellent quality; as a work of sterling merit; a
   man of sterling wit or good sense.

                                STERLING, n.

   1. English money.

   And Roman wealth in English sterling view.

   In this use, sterling may signify English coins.

   2. Standard; rate. [Little used in either sense.]
